 So, I got my business exposure that way.

34
00:03:03,180 --> 00:03:12,120
 That took me back to university where I was able to secure a degree in business administration and commerce.

35
00:03:12,420 --> 00:03:15,420
 So, that was a global supply chain on logistics management.

36
00:03:15,420 --> 00:03:20,520
 And through that, I started as an intern at GetFresh Ventures.

37
00:03:20,520 --> 00:03:24,220
 And that's where my journey kind of started from there.

38
00:03:24,220 --> 00:03:25,020
 And we can, yeah.

39
00:03:25,460 --> 00:03:31,940
 So, you started bringing, like, your career from interposition to all the way to VP position.

40
00:03:31,940 --> 00:03:33,160
 Yes.

41
00:03:33,160 --> 00:03:33,900
 Yeah.

42
00:03:33,900 --> 00:03:34,900
 Very interesting.

43
00:03:34,900 --> 00:03:39,720
 Maybe one interesting thing to mention as well is that in the high school, you were playing sports.

44
00:03:39,720 --> 00:03:46,700
 So, probably from there, you as well catch that discipline and to be consistent, to work hard.

45
00:03:47,200 --> 00:03:47,620
 Definitely.

46
00:03:47,620 --> 00:03:48,400
 Definitely.

47
00:03:48,400 --> 00:03:57,940
 Growing up, playing basketball and getting into martial arts, which got to teach me that motivation and sticking with something until the end.

48
00:03:57,940 --> 00:03:58,620
 Perfect.

49
00:03:58,620 --> 00:03:59,160
 Yeah.

50
00:03:59,160 --> 00:04:02,920
 So, if we are going now to touch a bit on the startup scene.

51
00:04:02,920 --> 00:04:05,960
 So, you work with thousands of startups.

52
00:04:05,960 --> 00:04:09,440
 Probably, just today, you talked more than 50 startups.

53
00:04:10,860 --> 00:04:17,160
 When a founder first pitched you, like, startup idea, what's the something that you're looking for there?

54
00:04:17,160 --> 00:04:18,560
 What are you listening to?

55
00:04:18,560 --> 00:04:27,500
 Are there any details, like, you want to catch in order to see if the idea is going to be successful or not?

56
00:04:27,500 --> 00:04:29,180
 That's a great question.

57
00:04:29,180 --> 00:04:29,700
 Yeah.

58
00:04:29,700 --> 00:04:32,140
 There's two main things that I'm looking for.

59
00:04:32,140 --> 00:04:37,200
 And I actually just gave this feedback earlier today, which was, what is the actual business impact?

60
00:04:37,200 --> 00:04:41,560
 What's the economic impact based on what you want to do in the market?

61
00:04:41,560 --> 00:04:44,260
 How are we going to make money?

62
00:04:44,260 --> 00:04:51,700
 Or how is the investor going to get their investment back, ideally with a high return?

63
00:04:51,700 --> 00:04:58,700
 Additionally, on the other side, I'm looking at, do you have a market that is captivated?

64
00:04:58,700 --> 00:05:04,800
 Do they care enough to buy your product and not even just buy it once, but buy it en masse?

65
00:05:04,800 --> 00:05:09,380
 Are they going to stay retained and continue to buy your product?

66
00:05:09,380 --> 00:05:11,900
 Or is it just going to be the one time?

67
00:05:11,900 --> 00:05:15,780
 How are we going to continually expand that market?

68
00:05:15,780 --> 00:05:20,280
 So, most important thing, in your opinion, would be kind of markets.

69
00:05:20,280 --> 00:05:25,360
 In which market they are operating and how big opportunity is there in the markets?

70
00:05:25,360 --> 00:05:26,300
 Yeah.

71
00:05:26,300 --> 00:05:29,900
 At times, it depends on the business that they want to build.

72
00:05:29,900 --> 00:05:35,220
 I like to start my conversations with founders being, hey, what do you actually want to do with this company?

73
00:05:35,220 --> 00:05:37,360
 Because a lot of founders are, they're in build mode.

74
00:05:37,360 --> 00:05:42,240
 They haven't had the chance to think, what do I actually want to build this into?

75
00:05:42,240 --> 00:05:44,880
 Do I want to exit with $5 million, go do it again?

76
00:05:44,880 --> 00:05:50,240
 Do I want to exit with $20 million, be able to go retire, chill on a beach in Montenegro?

77
00:05:50,680 --> 00:05:57,620
 Or do they want to swing for the fences and go for the, be the next Uber, be the next WeWork and such?

78
00:05:57,620 --> 00:05:59,540
 Which may be a bad example on that one.

79
00:05:59,540 --> 00:06:08,560
 But based on that, we can start to determine, well, what is the market size that we need to be able to get that exit that they want to have, right?

80
00:06:09,020 --> 00:06:26,560
 If you tell me you want to exit with $20 million, but the market size is not going to be able to allow that, perhaps we need to identify a different market segment that will allow them to achieve that exit that they want to get to.

81
00:06:27,100 --> 00:06:39,400
 But what is more important is less of the market size, but understanding the specific persona within that market that is going to buy that on a repeatable way.

82
00:06:39,400 --> 00:06:44,380
 So basically understanding the customer, understanding your customer and his wants.

83
00:06:44,380 --> 00:06:45,080
 Definitely.

84
00:06:45,080 --> 00:06:45,720
 Yeah.

85
00:06:45,720 --> 00:06:50,300
 Understanding their wants and being able to speak their language as well.

86
00:06:50,820 --> 00:07:01,940
 That's why I love talking to founders that have specific domain experience or they have done an extreme amount of research onto the market that they're targeting.

87
00:07:01,940 --> 00:07:15,420
 Instead of just building in a bubble and assuming that these are the things that their persona are going to want, they are actively in conversations with these customers that they want to sell to.

88
00:07:15,420 --> 00:07:17,320
 What do you think about passion?

89
00:07:18,100 --> 00:07:22,200
 Like in the way, do founders need to be very passionate about it?

90
00:07:22,200 --> 00:07:27,260
 And if they're a passion that success rates is higher or you have a different opinion on it?

91
00:07:27,260 --> 00:07:28,580
 It's a great question.

92
00:07:28,580 --> 00:07:39,100
 I think passion is something that is extremely important as long as it can sustain throughout the journey as well.

93
00:07:39,100 --> 00:07:52,940
 Passion at the beginning may help to start you off, but the entrepreneurship journey and the founder journey is full of peaks and valleys.

94
00:07:52,940 --> 00:08:05,440
 And having that motivation and that need to want to have that is definitely a key piece.

95
00:08:06,040 --> 00:08:07,360
 Yeah, very interesting.

96
00:08:07,360 --> 00:08:10,960
 What about, let's say, we have a good idea.

97
00:08:10,960 --> 00:08:12,680
 We have good market.

98
00:08:12,680 --> 00:08:14,140
 Market is open for us.

99
00:08:14,140 --> 00:08:15,780
 We understand our customer.

100
00:08:15,780 --> 00:08:17,820
 What are some, like, next steps?

101
00:08:17,820 --> 00:08:20,660
 Do we think in a way, okay, this is working.

102
00:08:21,120 --> 00:08:38,640
 I need one million to, or two million or 10 million to increase my business to get it rolling even more, or I need to bootstrap and go in the direction that, okay, we're going slowly, but we are alone, let's say.

103
00:08:38,900 --> 00:08:39,760
 Definitely, yeah.

104
00:08:39,760 --> 00:08:45,860
 I think it's very important to go back to that question of what do we want to do with this company, right?

105
00:08:45,860 --> 00:08:54,400
 Because that's going to feed the decision making on whether you raise and when you raise and how much you raise as well.

106
00:08:54,400 --> 00:09:16,900
 If you can verify your market and be able to start generating your early revenue by only getting around, you know, $50,000 to $100,000 to be able to get to that stage where you're generating your first revenue versus having to raise $1 million, diluting yourself to get to that first stage of revenue.

107
00:09:16,900 --> 00:09:23,920
 But reducing how much equity you have will ultimately reduce how much you're going to get at exit.

108
00:09:23,920 --> 00:09:32,420
 So maybe you're not going to be on a beach in the Caribbean and you might have to settle for a beach, a sandy beach in Vancouver.

109
00:09:32,420 --> 00:09:34,140
 So not bad, though.

110
00:09:34,140 --> 00:09:36,040
 Let's check on the other side.

111
00:09:36,040 --> 00:09:40,200
 What does, in your opinion, like a venture-ready startup look like?

112
00:09:40,200 --> 00:09:43,040
 Definitely, definitely.

113
00:09:43,040 --> 00:09:44,380
 Venture-ready startup.

114
00:09:45,920 --> 00:10:03,040
 So the venture scene from what I've seen over the past four and a half years is they're looking for companies that have that massive market that we're talking about where usually it's at least a billion plus, ideally even larger.

115
00:10:03,040 --> 00:10:08,020
 I know one of the companies that we're working with is in the travel space, which is about a $2 trillion market.

116
00:10:08,640 --> 00:10:31,220
 Now that's an opportunity where if you're coming in and generating any kind of revenue, let's say $100,000 or even a couple million, there is still room to expand because that market size is just so massive that even a sliver of that is going to be enough to generate the returns that they want to achieve.

117
00:10:31,640 --> 00:10:34,920
 And then additionally, so that's just on the market size.

118
00:10:34,920 --> 00:10:40,780
 And then additionally from there is they're going to care about those customers that we're talking about.

119
00:10:40,780 --> 00:10:47,940
 Do they, they'll want to have interviews with the customers that are actually buying the product that you're selling, product or service that you're selling.

120
00:10:48,300 --> 00:10:52,420
 And they'll want to understand, are they buying, what reasons are they buying this for?

121
00:10:52,420 --> 00:10:54,200
 And are they going to continue to buy that?

122
00:10:54,200 --> 00:10:59,860
 So in determining that, they're going to start to see all the metrics that you're tracking.

123
00:11:00,580 --> 00:11:06,320
 So in addition to just top line revenue, they're also going to be looking at, okay, what is our retention rate, right?

124
00:11:06,320 --> 00:11:12,580
 Is that, is it high enough that we can verify that they're not just buying it once and then churning?

125
00:11:12,580 --> 00:11:21,560
 Or are they continuing to buy this to the point where we're never going to lose them as a customer and their lifetime value is just massive?

126
00:11:21,560 --> 00:11:22,560
 That's increasing.

127
00:11:22,720 --> 00:11:29,200
 Yeah, so definitely going to get very metrics driven at the seed to series A level.

128
00:11:29,200 --> 00:11:34,280
 Pre-seed, you can definitely get away with some earlier traction.

129
00:11:34,280 --> 00:11:39,340
 But yeah, definitely at that seed to series A is where you start to know your numbers.

130
00:11:39,340 --> 00:11:46,020
 What are some common mistakes that you have seen in your journey working with startups when they want to scale?

131
00:11:46,580 --> 00:11:53,080
 Is it exactly this that they get funding and that they don't even think what are they going to do with it?

132
00:11:53,080 --> 00:11:59,640
 Or there are some different kind of paths that they're taking and that they're doing wrong in a way?

133
00:11:59,640 --> 00:11:59,920
 Yeah.

134
00:11:59,920 --> 00:12:10,460
 Depending, definitely I'll start, I'll move to the scale side, but I'll go back to kind of even the early stage is something I was touching on earlier,

135
00:12:10,460 --> 00:12:13,360
 which is building in a bubble, right?

136
00:12:13,360 --> 00:12:17,420
 Making sure that they're actively in conversations with their customers.

137
00:12:17,420 --> 00:12:22,000
 Not even just at that early stage, but also when you get to that scale stage.

138
00:12:22,000 --> 00:12:27,440
 At that scale stage, we start to understand and want to build almost a customer advisory board

139
00:12:27,440 --> 00:12:34,180
 is usually a very tactical way of implementing a lot of the feedback that you're getting from your customers

140
00:12:34,180 --> 00:12:42,260
 and making sure that you're pivoting and building your product roadmap based on the exact things that your customers,

141
00:12:42,260 --> 00:12:47,880
 who are the ones buying your product en masse, that they want and want to continue to see.

142
00:12:47,880 --> 00:12:54,120
 So I keep coming back to knowing your market and having that deep conversation with them,

143
00:12:54,120 --> 00:13:00,300
 but I think that's a very key component when it comes to scaling that startup and understanding it.

144
00:13:00,300 --> 00:13:05,200
 But also on the human side, making sure that you have the right people in the right seats, right?

145
00:13:05,200 --> 00:13:15,300
 If you have a thing that I was chatting with a founder with last week that I think could be beneficial

146
00:13:15,300 --> 00:13:21,780
 is build your first pitch deck, not for an investor.

147
00:13:21,780 --> 00:13:27,980
 Build that first pitch deck for yourself and your founding team.

148
00:13:28,100 --> 00:13:34,920
 If you can't convince yourself to invest in your time and your energy into that company,

149
00:13:34,920 --> 00:13:40,040
 then you may need to pivot or you may need to re-evaluate why you're doing this.

150
00:13:40,040 --> 00:13:45,420
 Because if you can't convince yourself or the rest of your team to invest in this, why would an investor?

151
00:13:45,420 --> 00:13:45,900
 Yeah.

152
00:13:45,900 --> 00:13:49,740
 Time is kind of the most valuable asset, right?

153
00:13:49,740 --> 00:13:53,080
 And it's not something that we can get back.

154
00:13:53,080 --> 00:13:54,620
 But money, money comes back.

155
00:13:54,620 --> 00:13:55,480
 If you find a way, yeah.

156
00:13:55,480 --> 00:13:56,600
 If you find a way to get that.

157
00:13:56,600 --> 00:13:57,600
 If I find a way, I'll call you.

158
00:13:57,600 --> 00:13:58,300
 Yeah, definitely.

159
00:13:58,300 --> 00:14:08,860
 In your articles and in general in the articles I mentioned you, I read that you kind of like that word repeatable revenue.

160
00:14:08,860 --> 00:14:10,920
 And you kind of use it a lot.

161
00:14:10,920 --> 00:14:19,540
 Can you tell us how can startups shift that early traction that they get, if they get early traction, into actually repeatable revenue?

162
00:14:21,100 --> 00:14:21,560
 Definitely.

163
00:14:21,560 --> 00:14:21,600
 Definitely.

164
00:14:21,600 --> 00:14:21,640
 Definitely.

165
00:14:21,640 --> 00:14:30,960
 I mean, it will definitely depend on what they're offering in the markets, whether it's something that can be repeatable.

166
00:14:30,960 --> 00:14:38,460
 But especially in the technology space, I would say about 60 to 70% of the companies we work with are B2B SaaS.

167
00:14:38,460 --> 00:14:49,520
 And a lot of the companies with that, they may not have a strategy yet on how they're going to build a recurring model associated with it.

168
00:14:49,520 --> 00:15:02,020
 And maybe it's a SaaS or a platform, whatever that may be, but building out that repeatable engine through a subscription service.

169
00:15:02,020 --> 00:15:15,700
 And even if you have to maybe sacrifice a little bit to get them on board for that, maybe it's giving the first three months free or maybe it is utilizing some interesting pricing models.

170
00:15:15,900 --> 00:15:17,600
 Giving some amount of credits, maybe.

171
00:15:17,600 --> 00:15:18,980
 Definitely, definitely.

172
00:15:18,980 --> 00:15:19,960
 You know all about that.

173
00:15:19,960 --> 00:15:31,460
 So there's a lot of strategies that you can do to secure them as a user, not just for that initial few months.

174
00:15:31,460 --> 00:15:40,720
 Because, yeah, you could have a customer and have them pay monthly for the first three months, but they may churn.

175
00:15:40,720 --> 00:15:51,760
 Versus, okay, we're going to sign them up for one year and we're going to give them three months free, but you've got them for a year and you've got opportunity to retain them.

176
00:15:51,760 --> 00:16:04,360
 But that's where, you know, the departments really come in and customer success becomes a very key component because if you're giving something away for free, you have to make sure that they recognize the value.

177
00:16:04,360 --> 00:16:09,600
 Otherwise, the brain just doesn't connect the two, right?

178
00:16:09,600 --> 00:16:13,840
 They need a motivation to get on there and utilize that platform or service.

179
00:16:13,840 --> 00:16:15,460
 Definitely, very good advice.

180
00:16:15,460 --> 00:16:28,780
 I mean, to touch upon what you said, even if 9 of 20, 80 of them churns, those two can become big customers and actually bring everything back from all other losses, right?

181
00:16:28,780 --> 00:16:36,760
 Definitely, yeah, and that's where, you know, the NPS score can start to come in where they become your sales team, right?

182
00:16:36,760 --> 00:16:51,720
 If you can create clientele and customers that want to continually recommend your service or your product to other people, you're reducing your customer acquisition cost dramatically.

183
00:16:52,360 --> 00:17:01,740
 And I don't know about you, but I buy, anytime one of my friends suggests something, I take it much more serious than I would when I'm getting Instagram ads on it.

184
00:17:01,740 --> 00:17:03,080
 Of course, word of mouth.

185
00:17:03,080 --> 00:17:04,040
 Exactly.

186
00:17:04,040 --> 00:17:06,300
 That's the way we run, so.

187
00:17:06,300 --> 00:17:10,600
 Brandon, you're VP of growth at Get Fresh Ventures.

188
00:17:10,600 --> 00:17:18,840
 I would like you to tell us how do you at Get Fresh Ventures help actually startups and how do you provide them that kind of support and help them scale?

189
00:17:18,840 --> 00:17:26,740
 On the other side, before this recording, you mentioned that you operate quite different than other VCs.

190
00:17:26,740 --> 00:17:29,280
 Can you touch upon that a bit?

191
00:17:29,280 --> 00:17:30,560
 Definitely, yes.

192
00:17:30,560 --> 00:17:40,800
 We coined the term venture catalyst, and I like that term because a lot of the companies that we do chat to and explain what we do,

193
00:17:40,800 --> 00:17:43,460
 it's hard for them to pinpoint.

194
00:17:43,640 --> 00:17:51,520
 When they say, okay, it sounds like an accelerator, it also sounds like you are a VC, it's a fun terminology to use.

195
00:17:51,520 --> 00:17:52,940
 Can you repeat the term?

196
00:17:52,940 --> 00:17:54,740
 Yeah, venture catalyst.

197
00:17:54,740 --> 00:17:55,880
 Venture catalyst.

198
00:17:55,880 --> 00:17:56,360
 Yeah.

199
00:17:56,360 --> 00:17:58,140
 Is that something you invented or?

200
00:17:58,140 --> 00:18:02,220
 My CEO came up with it and, yeah, supported it, yeah.

201
00:18:02,220 --> 00:18:04,580
 Came at it together.

202
00:18:04,580 --> 00:18:12,240
 So that is the terminology we've been using because our main goal is to catalyze growth, right?

203
00:18:12,240 --> 00:18:24,420
 And the issue, I don't know if there are certain companies that maybe aren't the right fit for venture capital, right?

204
00:18:24,760 --> 00:18:28,020
 We were chatting about that earlier on the massive market size.

205
00:18:28,020 --> 00:18:35,400
 There is an opportunity for a lot of different businesses to grow depending on what that founder's goals are.

206
00:18:35,400 --> 00:18:46,400
 Perhaps instead of becoming a venture-backed company, you want to just build a company that's going to generate you $100,000 in annual recurring revenue

207
00:18:46,400 --> 00:18:50,620
 that you're able to now do whatever else it is that you want to do.

208
00:18:50,620 --> 00:18:56,680
 And that might be your goal, but that's not going to be a good fit for venture capital.

209
00:18:56,680 --> 00:19:05,680
 So what we do is we partner with those founders and understand what those goals are and help them achieve that.

210
00:19:05,680 --> 00:19:10,860
 So, again, if they want to become a venture-backable company, we'll do the math.

211
00:19:10,860 --> 00:19:16,720
 We'll figure out whether that is possible and build them the roadmap to get there and guide them along the way.

212
00:19:16,720 --> 00:19:23,380
 So it's a lot of growth coaching, executive coaching, and growth advisory.

213
00:19:23,380 --> 00:19:27,720
 We got to that stage when I first started with the company.

214
00:19:27,720 --> 00:19:30,300
 We were doing fractional growth officer services.

215
00:19:30,300 --> 00:19:36,920
 We were an extension of the C-suite and really integrated within all the different departments within a company.

216
00:19:36,920 --> 00:19:43,240
 But we wanted to impact more companies, which is why we shifted to that advisory model.

217
00:19:43,240 --> 00:19:46,300
 But we didn't want to do it en masse.

218
00:19:46,300 --> 00:19:51,700
 We wanted to make sure that every single company we were working with, we were putting in 110% effort

219
00:19:51,700 --> 00:20:02,980
 because there is the power law that does happen in venture capital where probably 10% of the companies are going to return the investment

220
00:20:02,980 --> 00:20:07,500
 and then maybe one or two might be a unicorn while the other 90% may not make it.

221
00:20:07,500 --> 00:20:09,380
 We want to see them all succeed, right?

222
00:20:09,380 --> 00:20:10,460
 You're building a business.

223
00:20:10,460 --> 00:20:14,300
 You likely are putting in, we were chatting about that, you're never going to get time back.

224
00:20:14,300 --> 00:20:15,660
 You're putting in that time.

225
00:20:15,660 --> 00:20:16,620
 You're putting in that effort.

226
00:20:16,620 --> 00:20:23,700
 We want to make sure every founder is successful and that they are exiting with what they want to achieve with that company.

227
00:20:23,700 --> 00:20:25,920
 Very interesting.

228
00:20:25,920 --> 00:20:32,260
 When we talk about like you have startups that join you and want to get funding.

229
00:20:32,260 --> 00:20:37,100
 You have startups that join you and they're maybe just bootstrapping and want to help you scale.

230
00:20:37,100 --> 00:20:38,560
 You help them scale.

231
00:20:38,560 --> 00:20:42,200
 In the way, how picky are you in your portfolio?

232
00:20:42,200 --> 00:20:45,920
 In the way, do you do more like the companies that are looking for funding?

233
00:20:45,920 --> 00:20:48,700
 Or do you more go for companies that are bootstrapping?

234
00:20:48,700 --> 00:20:50,280
 Yeah.

235
00:20:50,280 --> 00:21:00,500
 Both are okay and we're happy to work with both types of companies depending on what their goals are as a founding team.

236
00:21:00,500 --> 00:21:11,000
 We typically want to work with companies before they go to a fundraise because if they're coming to us and actively fundraising, we can definitely help.

237
00:21:11,000 --> 00:21:25,560
 But the real work that gets done is getting that business to the stage where we understand the business well enough to position it in the market rather than you're coming to us already positioned in the market.

238
00:21:25,560 --> 00:21:34,540
 And we now have to make some major pivots that we could have figured out three, four months prior by starting early.

239
00:21:34,540 --> 00:21:36,920
 Interesting.

240
00:21:36,920 --> 00:21:45,640
 What is maybe some advice that you would like to give to young founders that are just starting the company and that are just bringing that idea to life?

241
00:21:46,200 --> 00:21:46,700
 Definitely, definitely.

242
00:21:46,700 --> 00:21:47,260
 Definitely, definitely.

243
00:21:47,260 --> 00:21:54,500
 Just do it.

244
00:21:54,500 --> 00:22:02,540
 It's a big one, of course, but understand why you want to do that as well, right?

245
00:22:02,620 --> 00:22:06,260
 I keep coming back to that of entrepreneurs are builders.

246
00:22:06,260 --> 00:22:10,520
 They're builders first, typically visionaries as well.

247
00:22:10,520 --> 00:22:25,800
 They see the eventual goal of what they want to build that company into, but that company that you're building is also your path to your net worth, right?

248
00:22:25,800 --> 00:22:34,760
 And what you want to do with that company, you need to understand what that is from the beginning because you're going to have to communicate it to investors along the way.

249
00:22:34,760 --> 00:22:39,160
 And if you don't have an exit, start planning your exit immediately.

250
00:22:39,160 --> 00:22:44,780
 Understand what you're going to build this company into and you can start to build the roadmap to get there.

251
00:22:45,420 --> 00:22:53,620
 And it might be an acquisition and for $5 million, $10 million and great, that's a great first business and great first exit.

252
00:22:53,620 --> 00:22:56,740
 Or maybe it's something different.

253
00:22:56,740 --> 00:23:07,000
 You build a lifestyle business that is going to generate you $50,000, $60,000 a year, which is not anything to knock on.

254
00:23:07,000 --> 00:23:10,700
 And that may free you up to focus on other things.

255
00:23:10,700 --> 00:23:18,020
 So, I think build, but understand why you're building so that you can stay motivated throughout that journey.

256
00:23:18,020 --> 00:23:25,320
 So, have that passion, know the market size, know the market fit, find the right market and just go for it.

257
00:23:25,320 --> 00:23:29,420
 Even if you lose, you learned a lot.

258
00:23:29,420 --> 00:23:33,620
 So, on the next stage, you probably know what mistakes not to make, right?

259
00:23:33,620 --> 00:23:34,740
 Definitely, definitely.

260
00:23:34,740 --> 00:23:39,180
 It helps to fall down a couple times to get back up.

261
00:23:39,180 --> 00:23:43,520
 I know I've fallen down many times and I've always learned from it, right?

262
00:23:43,520 --> 00:23:47,380
 And staying open to that learning definitely makes sense.

263
00:23:47,380 --> 00:23:53,640
 But don't always just, I do want to say, don't always just push through and continue to push through.

264
00:23:53,640 --> 00:23:55,220
 Be aware.

265
00:23:55,220 --> 00:24:02,260
 Always have a mentor that you're working with that is going to guide you when it's time to truly pivot.

266
00:24:02,260 --> 00:24:12,140
 Because you can continue to be pushing down a path and I think that's great for muscle memory to learn how to roll with the punches.

267
00:24:12,140 --> 00:24:19,740
 But also, it's good to have somebody with a separate point of view that's able to say, hey, it is time for you to pivot.

268
00:24:19,740 --> 00:24:26,680
 You've done very well, but it's time for you to either pivot what you're doing right now or drop it.

269
00:24:27,200 --> 00:24:27,920
 And that's okay.

270
00:24:27,920 --> 00:24:31,140
 How important is the mentorship in the whole journey?

271
00:24:31,140 --> 00:24:33,040
 Massive.

272
00:24:33,040 --> 00:24:34,040
 Massive.

273
00:24:34,040 --> 00:24:38,680
 So, I mean, mentorship has really driven me to where I am today.

274
00:24:38,680 --> 00:24:46,800
 If I didn't have mentors throughout my career journey, I'm not too, too sure what I'd be doing.

275
00:24:46,800 --> 00:24:51,520
 But I definitely wouldn't be at the current stage that I am in my career.

276
00:24:51,940 --> 00:24:53,840
 Can you give us some examples, maybe?

277
00:24:53,840 --> 00:24:54,500
 Definitely.

