00:24:57,920 --> 00:25:06,600
 So, one of my key mentors, who is now a very good friend of mine, he met me while I was in hospitality.

281
00:25:06,600 --> 00:25:22,180
 So, I was bartending at the time and took a shine to me and realized that there was a skill set that I had been developing and wanted to encourage me to explore it more.

282
00:25:22,180 --> 00:25:24,120
 And that was business.

283
00:25:24,440 --> 00:25:28,180
 And I'd never considered that in the past whatsoever.

284
00:25:28,180 --> 00:25:32,340
 Like I say, no exposure except like a long-distance second cousin.

285
00:25:32,340 --> 00:25:34,300
 So, for me, I'm like, this is interesting.

286
00:25:34,300 --> 00:25:49,300
 So, but through my conversations with them, they really helped open my mind up to what that really could be and what the future might be if I decided to pursue that.

287
00:25:49,300 --> 00:26:02,180
 So, in addition to opening my eyes, it was also that support system that I needed and supported me in writing my application and ultimately getting into one of the top business schools in Canada.

288
00:26:03,180 --> 00:26:07,520
 And that's mentorship definitely drove that result.

289
00:26:07,520 --> 00:26:10,540
 And throughout my journey, that's been the same way.

290
00:26:10,540 --> 00:26:15,020
 I mean, you know, we mentioned that I'm a vice president of growth, that I get fresh.

291
00:26:15,020 --> 00:26:32,860
 But when I started as an intern, right, and continually looking for opportunities to grow within the company, right, I took four or five promotions, something like that, because I just identify areas that the business needed support and I would just own that area.

292
00:26:33,180 --> 00:26:48,720
 And I continued to do that because that gave me that exposure and I would likely not have done that had I not had the mentorship and the leadership from my team as well as my mentors externally.

293
00:26:49,440 --> 00:26:57,240
 Yeah, usually when we say and mention mentors, people always associate it with lots of money, you need to pay lots of money to them.

294
00:26:57,240 --> 00:26:59,980
 And it's like time consuming and money consuming.

295
00:26:59,980 --> 00:27:03,820
 But actually, it's not something that you have to always pay.

296
00:27:03,820 --> 00:27:08,380
 Like, you can find mentors from lots of people around you in the way.

297
00:27:08,900 --> 00:27:20,300
 Like, I don't know, for me, for example, I'm a student, I find the mentors in my professors that are successful, that work good, and they're always there to give advice, to talk, you know, you can ask them always something.

298
00:27:20,300 --> 00:27:26,780
 Same in the company, like you find people that are on the bigger position than you that know what they're doing.

299
00:27:26,780 --> 00:27:31,020
 So you kind of mimic them, try to do it your way, you know, catch that.

300
00:27:31,020 --> 00:27:34,580
 So it's not always about money and mentorship, like paying for it.

301
00:27:34,580 --> 00:27:36,160
 You can always find it like around.

302
00:27:36,600 --> 00:27:40,140
 Definitely. I think giving back is the biggest thing, because that's what I've learned.

303
00:27:40,140 --> 00:27:44,640
 Being a mentee has driven me to become a mentor myself.

304
00:27:44,640 --> 00:27:59,860
 So any opportunity I get to mentor people that are at the earlier stages of their career or even, you know, in a certain area that I have expertise, I'm always happy to have time for them.

305
00:27:59,860 --> 00:28:02,380
 And a lot of the times it's chatting with startups.

306
00:28:02,380 --> 00:28:18,840
 Yes, we do run a service where we do, we are paid for our advisory services, but the mentorship that I'm able to give to startups is something that's honestly rewarding for myself to do and seems to help a lot of the startups as well.

307
00:28:18,840 --> 00:28:21,340
 So mentorship is a key component of that.

308
00:28:21,560 --> 00:28:27,920
 And I think every founder and honestly, every person should probably have a mentor.

309
00:28:27,920 --> 00:28:28,920
 Yeah.

